    "client_msg_id": "0f114bd1-833c-423f-b9f9-bb4167ddba44",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "I have little context on the modern iterations of these languages and am trying to attribute _some_ reason as to why they split in popularity. The few thoughts that came to mind:\n• Lisp is a standard and the dialects can be more flexible / meet modern use cases. \n• COBOL found a home on mainframes which are rarely used outside of banking\n• Fortran found an early footing in academic systems and has only been a stable, reliable base for scientific computing. Also performance\nDo any of those points hold water?",
    "user": "U055V4HCHU7",
    "ts": "1688056383.699989",
